00:07:32.130 --> 00:07:34.290
And I haven't really said
what the ends are.

00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:37.290
So the ends are just all the
way to the left and all the

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:37.940
way to the right.

00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:42.670
So that means x going to
plus or minus infinity.

00:07:42.670 --> 00:07:44.430
So that's the second thing I
want to pay attention to.

00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:49.450
Again, this is a little bit
like a video screen here.

00:07:49.450 --> 00:07:52.720
And we're about to discover
something that's really off

00:07:52.720 --> 00:07:55.750
the screen, in both cases.

00:07:55.750 --> 00:07:58.070
We're taking care of what's
happening way to the left, way

00:07:58.070 --> 00:07:59.360
to the right, here.

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:01.820
And up above, we just took
care what happens

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:05.280
way up and way down.

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:11.550
So on these ends, I need to
do some more analysis.

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:15.760
Which is related to a
precalculus skill which is

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:18.310
evaluating limits.

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:21.950
And here, the way to do it is
to divide by x the numerator

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:23.010
and denominator.

00:08:23.010 --> 00:08:27.360
Write it as (1 + 1
/ x)/ (1 + 2 /x).

00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:30.250
And then you can see what
happens as x goes to plus or

00:08:30.250 --> 00:08:30.980
minus infinity.

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:33.590
It just goes to 1.

00:08:33.590 --> 00:08:37.690
So, no matter whether x is
positive or negative.

00:08:37.690 --> 00:08:42.810
When it gets huge, these two
extra numbers here go to 0.

00:08:42.810 --> 00:08:44.550
And so, this tends to 1.

00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:48.450
So if you like, you could
abbreviate this as f (+ or -

00:08:48.450 --> 00:08:52.830
infinity) = 1.

00:08:52.830 --> 00:08:54.610
So now, I get to draw this.

00:08:54.610 --> 00:08:56.900
And we draw this using
asymptotes.

00:08:56.900 --> 00:09:01.800
So there's a level
which is y = 1.

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:06.790
And then there's another
line to draw.

00:09:06.790 --> 00:09:15.190
Which is x = - 2.

00:09:15.190 --> 00:09:18.520
And now, what information
do I have so far?

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:21.260
Well, the information that I
have so far is that when we're

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:27.760
coming in from the right, that's
to - 2, it plunges down

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:28.570
to minus infinity.

00:09:28.570 --> 00:09:33.170
So that's down like this.

00:09:33.170 --> 00:09:38.810
And I also know that it goes
up to infinity on the other

00:09:38.810 --> 00:09:41.850
side of the asymptote.

00:09:41.850 --> 00:09:48.130
And over here, I know it's
going out to the level 1.

00:09:48.130 --> 00:09:53.410
And here it's also going
to the level 1.

00:09:53.410 --> 00:09:57.160
Now, there's an issue.

00:09:57.160 --> 00:09:59.490
I can almost finish
this graph now.

00:09:59.490 --> 00:10:01.460
I almost have enough information
to finish it.

00:10:01.460 --> 00:10:03.890
But there's one thing
which is making me

00:10:03.890 --> 00:10:06.780
hesitate a little bit.

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:10.600
And that is, I don't know, for
instance, over here, whether

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:14.230
it's going to maybe dip below
and come back up.

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:16.930
Or not.

00:10:16.930 --> 00:10:20.140
So what does it do here?

00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:25.040
Can anybody see?

00:10:25.040 --> 00:10:25.250
Yeah.

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:29.900
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:32.220
PROFESSOR: It can't dip
below because there

00:10:32.220 --> 00:10:32.380
are no critical points.

00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:34.540
What a precisely
correct answer.

00:10:34.540 --> 00:10:36.730
So that's exactly right.

00:10:36.730 --> 00:10:44.260
The point here is that because
f' is not 0, it can't double

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:45.020
back on itself.

00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:49.790
Because there can't be any of
these horizontal tangents.

00:10:49.790 --> 00:11:00.560
It can't double back, so
it can't backtrack.

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:07.190
So sorry, if f' is not
0, f can't backtrack.

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:09.410
And so that means that it
doesn't look like this.

00:11:09.410 --> 00:11:14.320
It just goes like this.

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:15.690
So that's basically it.

00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:17.630
And it's practically the
end of the problem.

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:19.500
Goes like this.

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:21.870
Now you can decorate
your thing, right?

00:11:21.870 --> 00:11:24.540
You may notice that maybe it
crosses here, the axes, you

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:26.790
can actually evaluate
these places.

00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:27.500
And so forth.

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:31.130
We're looking right now for
qualitative behavior.

00:11:31.130 --> 00:11:34.280
In fact, you can see where
these places hit.

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:36.660
And it's actually a little
higher up than I drew.

00:11:36.660 --> 00:11:40.140
Maybe I'll draw it accurately.

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:44.970
As we'll see in a second.

00:11:44.970 --> 00:11:47.710
So that's what happens
to this function.

00:11:47.710 --> 00:11:51.990
Now, let's just take a look in
a little bit more detail, by

00:11:51.990 --> 00:11:56.840
double checking.

00:11:56.840 --> 00:11:58.990
So we're just going to double
check what happens to the sign

00:11:58.990 --> 00:12:01.280
of the derivative.

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:03.830
And in the meantime, I'm going
to explain to you what the

00:12:03.830 --> 00:12:07.045
